|depth=
|discoverer=''[[Cassini–Huygens|Cassini]]''
|naming=[[Az-Zahir (caliph)|Az-Zahir]]; Abbasid Caliph
}}

'''Al-Mustazi''' is an [[impact crater]] located on the anti-Saturn hemisphere of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]].  Al-Mustazi was first observed in ''[[Cassini-Huygens Mission|Cassini]]'' images during that mission's March 2005 flyby of Enceladus.  It is located at 20.9° South [[Latitude]], 202.0° West [[Longitude]], and is 10.3 kilometers across.<ref name="USGS"/>  ''Cassini'' observed numerous southwest-northeast trending fractures cutting across the southwest rim of Al-Mustazi, forming canyons several hundred meters deep.  These fractures were deflected by the weakened [[regolith]] produced by the Al-Mustazi impact.<ref name=Barnash>A. N. Barnash ''et al.'' (2006). "[http://www.abstractsonline.com/viewer/viewAbstract.asp?CKey={25BDAB68-CDB8-47D3-A19C-D0FFD5D11E58}&MKey={66F0352A-30DC-4B9F-B0CC-E851495B78DC}&AKey={AAF9AABA-B0FF-4235-8AEC-74F22FC76386}&SKey={C4707917-6E8C-4620-9DC2-2A702863D08D} Interactions Between Impact Craters and Tectonic Fractures on Enceladus]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}". ''Bull. Am. Astron. Soc.'' '''38''' (3): Presentation Num. 24.06.</ref>  This deflection produced the pattern of radiating fractures seen along the northeastern rim of Al-Mustazi. 

Al-Mustazi is named after [[Az-Zahir (caliph)|Az-Zahir]], a 13th-century Abbasid caliph and a character in "[[The Hunchback's Tale]]" from ''[[The Book of One Thousand and One Nights]]''.

