A '''bacterial consorm''' or '''bacterial community''' is a group of different types of [[bacteria]] - within a [[Biomass (ecology)|biomass]] - that summatively act as a unit, with each type of bacteria contributing to the function of the consorm (community).<ref name='identification'>{{cite book | last1 = Cullimore | first1 = D. Roy | title = Practical Atlas for Bacterial Identification | chapter = 1 Bacterial Communities by Location and Function | edition = Second | publisher = CRC Press | year = 2010 | pages = 1–9 | url = http://www.crcnetbase.com/doi/pdf/10.1201/9781420087987-c1 | accessdate = 2012-01-11 | id = 10.1201/9781420087987-c1 | isbn = 978-1-4200-8798-7}}</ref>
This is a rarely used term that is mostly synonymous to [[Microbial consortium|consortium]].
