{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}

'''Edward M. Stricker''' is an American neuroscientist, currently a University Professor at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and formerly Dean at its [[University_of_Pittsburgh_Honors_College|Honors College]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Edward M. Stricker, Ph.D. |url=https://neuroscience.pitt.edu/people/edward-m-stricker-phd |publisher=University of Pittsburgh |website=Department of Neuroscience |access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Edward Stricker steps down as Honors College dean |url=https://pittnews.com/article/108845/top-stories/edward-stricker-steps-honors-college-dean/ |author=Alexa Bakalarski |date=June 21, 2016 |website=The Pitt News |access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref>

Professor Stricker (born {{Birth year and age|1941}} in New York, NY) earned a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1960, a master's degree in chemistry from that same institution in 1961, and a PhD in psychology from [[Yale University]] in 1965.  He held faculty positions at [[McMaster University]] in Hamilton, Ontario from 1967 to 1971, and at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] from 1971 to 1986, before being named University Professor in 1986.<ref name="ppg2016">{{cite news |last1=Danielewski |first1=Mike |title=Pitt University Honors College dean to return to teaching |url=https://www.post-gazette.com/news/education/2016/06/16/Pitt-University-Honors-College-dean-announces-return-to-faculty/stories/201606170065 |accessdate=1 December 2018 |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=16 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref>

His research career spanned four decades and focused on various aspects of [[homeostasis]], most prominently the physiological and behavioral contributions to body [[fluid balance]],<ref>{{cite journal |last= Stricker |first= Edward M |last2= Verbalis |first2= Joseph G |date= 1988|title= Hormones and behavior: The biology of thirst and sodium appetite |journal= [[American Scientist]] |publisher= Sigma Xi |volume= 76 |issue= 3 |pages= 261–267 |jstor= 27855183}}</ref> and recovery of function following damage to brain [[Catecholamine|catecholamine]]-containing neurons.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Zigmond |first= Michael J |author-link= Michael J. Zigmond |last2= Abercrombie |first2= Elizabeth D |last3= Berger |first3= Theodore W |last4= Grace |first4= Anthony A |author-link4= Anthony A. Grace |last5= Stricker |first5= Edward M |date= July 1990 |title= Compensations after lesions of central dopaminergic neurons: some clinical and basic implications |journal= [[Trends in Neurosciences]] |volume= 13 |issue= 7 |pages= 290–296 |doi= 10.1016/0166-2236(90)90112-N |issn= 0166-2236 |pmid= 1695406}}</ref>  For this work he received the research scientist award from the U.S. [[National Institute of Mental Health]] (1981-1986) and the distinguished career award from the [[Society_for_the_Study_of_Ingestive_Behavior|Society for the Study of Ingestive Behavior]] (2015).<ref>{{cite journal |last= Stricker |first= Edward M |date= 2016 |title= 2015 Distinguished career award: Reflections on a career in science |journal= [[Physiology & Behavior]] |volume= 162
|pages= 196–200 |doi= 10.1016/j.physbeh.2015.09.028 |pmc= 4955950 |pmid= 26434784}}</ref>

During his academic career, Stricker has served in various administrative roles at the University of Pittsburgh, including director of the behavioral neuroscience program (1983-1986), founding chair of the department of neuroscience (1986-2002), founding director of the center for neuroscience and schizophrenia (1990-1995), co-director of the center for neuroscience (1996-2002), and Dean of the [[University_of_Pittsburgh_Honors_College|University Honors College]] (2011-2017).

His teaching ranged from introductory courses to graduate courses in neuroscience, as well as interdisciplinary honors courses. In recognition of his teaching, the University of Pittsburgh has awarded him the 2001 Tina & David Bellet Teaching Excellence Award and 1992 Chancellor's Distinguished Teaching Award.<ref name="ppg2016" />

