{{Infobox person |name = Grace Frankland |image = Mrs_Percy_Frankland_born_Grace_Toynbee_died_1946.png |image_size = |birth_name = Grace Coleridge Toynbee |birth_date = {{birth date|1858|12|04|df=yes}} |birth_place = Wimbledon |death_date = {{death date and age|1946|10|05|1858|12|04|df=yes}} |death_place = [[Loch Awe]], [[Argyll]] |nationality = English |other_names = Mrs Percy Frankland |known_for = [[Bacteriology]] }} '''Grace Coleridge Frankland''' known as '''Mrs Percy Frankland''' ''née'' Grace Toynbee (4 December 1858 – 5 October 1946)<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|title=Grace Frankland|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/62/101062321/|work=ODNB}}</ref> was an English microbiologist. She was one of the nineteen female scientists who wrote the [[1904 petition to the Chemical Society]] to request that they should create some female fellows of the society.
==Life== She was the daughter (and youngest of nine children) of Harriet and [[Joseph Toynbee]], a noted [[otology|otologist]]. She was home schooled and spent one year at Bedford College<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/665046168|title=Chemistry was their life : pioneering British women chemists, 1880-1949|last=F.|first=Rayner-Canham, Marelene|date=2008|publisher=Imperial College Press|others=Rayner-Canham, Geoffrey.|isbn=186094986X|location=London|oclc=665046168}}</ref>, She married [[Percy Frankland]] in 1882, and with him developed an interest in the emerging science of [[bacteriology]]. She worked with both Percy and his father [[Edward Frankland]] and was described at the time as having "worthily aided and seconded [Percy]".<ref>Quoted in {{cite book|last=Rayner-Canham|title=Chemistry was their life: Pioneer British women chemists, 1880-1949|year=2008|publisher=Imperial College Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-86094-986-9|pages=424|author2=Marelene F. Rayner-Canham |author3=Geoffrey Rayner-Canham }}</ref> She co-authored papers with her husband on bacteria and other microorganisms found in the air<ref>{{cite web|title=Studies on new Micro-organisms obtained from air|url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/91702?uid=3738032&uid=2&uid=4&sid=21101382927027}}</ref> and water.<ref>Frankland, Percy; Frankland, Grace Coleridge Toynbee. "Micro-organisms in water: their significance, identification and removal, together with an account of the bacteriological methods employed in their investigation, specially designed for the use of those connected with the sanitary aspects of water-supply." Longmans, Green, 1894.</ref> Colleagues of her husband noted that although their situation as husband and wife working equally together was not unique, he was 'the first man who had the chilvalry to admit it.'<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/36386419|title=Ladies in the laboratory? : American and British women in science, 1800-1900 : a survey of their contributions to research|last=1935-|first=Creese, Mary R. S.,|date=1998|publisher=Scarecrow Press|others=Creese, Thomas M.|isbn=0810832879|location=Lanham, Md.|oclc=36386419}}</ref>
In 1903 she wrote a popular science book entitled ''Bacteria in Daily Life''. It was written in an open style to engage a wide audience<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 18, 1903|title=Reviews|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2513022/pdf/brmedj08244-0026.pdf|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=1|pages=|via=|pmc=2513022|page=918-919|issue=2207}}</ref> and included important bacterial information pertaining to food, drink, smoking, pollution, sewage, air and disease. The book was reviewed in [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] in 1903
"''an interesting, instructive, and accurate account of the modern developments of bacteriology. Such subjects as sewage disposal, the prevention of tuberculosis, micro-organisms in milk, air, and foods, which are of public importance, are fully dealt with. ......No one nowadays laying claim to a liberal education can dispense with a slight knowledge, at least, of microbes and their actions, and for such this work will prove an adequate text-book."''<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v67/n1747/abs/067583b0.html?foxtrotcallback=true|title=Bacteria in Daily Life : Abstract : Nature|access-date=2017-07-28 | volume=67|doi=10.1038/067583b0|year=1903|journal=Nature|page=583 | last1 = Hewlett | first1 = R. T.}}</ref>
She was a Fellow of the [[Royal Microscopical Society]], admitted into the [[Linnean Society of London]], and an honorary member of [[Bedford College (London)|Bedford College]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bacteria in daily life|url=https://archive.org/stream/bacteriaindaily02frangoog#page/n6/mode/2up}}</ref> Her application in 1904 to the [[Chemical Society]] was important.<ref name="ODNB" /> She was one of the nineteen signatories of the [[1904 petition to the Chemical Society]]. These prominent female chemists set out the reasons why they should be afforded the status of Fellow.<ref name="RCPounding">{{cite journal|last1=Rayner-Canham|first1=Marelene|last2=Rayner-Canham|first2=Geoff|title=Pounding on the Doors: The Fight For Acceptance of British Women Chemists|journal=Bull. Hist. Chem.|volume=28|issue=2|pages=110-119}}</ref> The petition eventually led to the admission of women as Fellows of the Society<ref name="Mason 1991">{{cite journal|last1=Mason|first1=Joan|title=A forty years' war|journal=Chemistry in Britain|date=1991|pages=233-238}}</ref> (one of the Societies that amalgamated to become the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]]).<ref name="RCPounding" /><ref name="Creese1991">{{cite journal|last1=Creese|first1=Mary R. S.|title=British women of the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries who contributed to research in the chemical sciences|journal=The British Journal for the History of Science|date=5 January 2009|volume=24|issue=03|pages=275|doi=10.1017/S0007087400027370}}</ref>
Percy held positions as professor of Chemistry Birmingham, and Dundee universities. They lived in Dundee before retiring to Argyll<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zs6qBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA126&lpg=PA126&dq=grace+frankland+dundee&source=bl&ots=FYxIzgAwk3&sig=okb2vo1NRMteQH0figA1mVnu4Jw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQvObzgKzVAhWBWRoKHfsIAG0Q6AEISTAG#v=onepage&q=grace%20frankland%20dundee&f=false|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Scottish Women|last=Ewan|first=Elizabeth L.|last2=Innes|first2=Sue|last3=Reynolds|first3=Sian|last4=Pipes|first4=Rose|date=2006-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=9780748626601|language=en}}</ref>. As a result of their time in Dundee Grace is commemorated as part of Dundee Women's Trail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dundeewomenstrail.org.uk/frankland-grace-nee-toynbee-chemist-activist/|title=Frankland, Grace née Toynbee – Chemist, Activist {{!}} Dundee Women's Trail|website=www.dundeewomenstrail.org.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-28}}</ref>
Grace Frankland's papers are part of the Frankland family papers, held by the [[University of Manchester Library|University of Manchester]] Library.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.library.manchester.ac.uk/search-resources/guide-to-special-collections/atoz/sir-edward-frankland-papers/|title=Frankland, Sir Edward, Papers (The University of Manchester Library)|website=www.library.manchester.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-06-12}}</ref> <!-- can't find much online about her early or later life-->
